Ernan Lopez-Nussa - Delirium
1999

Brought to you by TQMP
The Quality Music Project

His extraordinary CD &quot;Delirium,&quot; which is difficult to come by in the U.S., points to a pianist who communicates in telegraphic bursts of sound, an artist who clearly prefers to hint at an idea rather than spell it out. The radical ways that Lopez-Nussa reworks everything from Wayne Shorter's &quot;Footprints&quot; to John Coltrane's &quot;Count Down,&quot; the ingenuity with which he unfolds quirky original compositions such as &quot;Lobo's Cha&quot; and &quot;Rumba Para Zapateo y Haydn&quot; affirm that Lopez-Nussa is every bit as much composer-arranger as pianist-improviser.
-- Chicago Tribune

